[2] St. Martin
Date: Fri 17 Oct 2008
Source: Institut de Veille Sanitaire, Point Epidemiologique no. 25
[in French, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/presse/2008/le_point_sur/dengue_pep_st_barth_171008/pep_sbsm_2008_25_dengue.pdf>


The rapid and significant increase in clinical [dengue] cases
continued during the 1st week of October [2008], with 230 cases
estimated during this week alone. A decline was observed during the
2nd week of October (150 cases). The increase in cases that were
laboratory confirmed followed a similar dynamic. However, the number
of cases recorded during the 3rd week of October (8 cases) remains
high, but still above the maximum expected for this period.

Laboratory confirmed [dengue] cases are spread over the whole island.
In total, 8 people were hospitalized in September [2008] (37 percent
of which were of severe forms [of the disease]). Since early October
2008, no hospitalizations have been recorded.

Since early September [2008] the DEN-2 [virus] serotype was
identified but [the number of virus serotypes] increased (5 DEN-2 and 3 DEN-1).

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This report comes from the French-administered side of the island.
The reported 37 percent of severe dengue cases is high, suggesting
that the WHO criteria were not being applied or there is significant
under-reporting of cases. - Mod.TY]

******
[3] Saba
Date: Tue 7 Oct 2008
Source: St. Maarten Island Time, The Daily Herald report [edited]
<http://www.sxmislandtime.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3411:dengue-epidemic-in-saba-with-nine-confirmed-cases&catid=31:general&Itemid=76www.sxmislandtime.com>


According to island doctors Jack Buchanan and Gys Koot, 9 cases of
dengue fever have been confirmed on Saba, and this constitutes an
epidemic. Both doctors are expecting additional cases.

A screening test is 1st done on the French side of St. Maarten,
followed by more in-depth testing at the Diagnostic Center in
Curacao. So far, 20 individuals have been tested.

Of these, 9 tested positive for the disease [virus or antibody]. None
of the cases so far have been of the hemorrhagic variety, and only 2
persons had been hospitalized.

Of the 2 persons who were hospitalized, one of them had never left
Saba. In another case, 3 family members had a complaint [that took
them] to the doctor. All were later confirmed to have dengue fever,
and all had been to Orient Beach.

The doctors are currently assuming that Saba's dengue originated in
St. Maarten, and was probably brought to Saba by infected persons.
Rudolph Johnson, head of mosquito control, said that it is a very
unusual situation, since he has heard of only one case of dengue in
Saba since he started work in 1971.

Johnson has posted extra notices and has increased home inspections.
He appealed to homeowners to be vigilant that there is no standing
water around their homes.

Stagnant water for flower arrangements must be changed daily to wash
out possible larvae deposits. Recent rains could have activated the
mosquito eggs, which could lie dormant for months.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The appearance of dengue on Saba Island, presumably imported from
the outbreak on St. Martin, indicates the ease with which people
transport the virus to new sites where vector populations are
adequate to permit ongoing virus transmission.

Saba is the smallest island of the Netherlands Antilles, located at
17 38 N, 63 14 W, (east of Puerto Rico and 28 mi (45 km) south of St.
Maarten). It consists largely of the dormant volcano Mount Scenery
(888 m), the highest point of the Kingdom of the Netherlands. Saba
has a land area of 13 sq. km (5 sq. miles). At the 2001 Netherlands
Antilles census, the population was 1349 inhabitants, which means a
population density of 104 inhabitants per sq. km. In 2004, the
population was estimated at 1424 inhabitants (information from the
Saba government
<http://www.sabagov.com/aboutsaba>.)

Saba can be located on the map at
<http://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/carib.htm>. - Mod.TY]

