[8] Viet Nam
Date: Sat 25 Oct 2008
Source: Thanh Nien News [edited]
<http://www.thanhniennews.com/healthy/?catid=8&newsid=43171>


The number of cases of dengue fever has surged over the last year
[2007], and health officials say the dreaded disease is now showing
greater complications. Dengue fever in Ho Chi Minh City [HCMC] has
increased dramatically this year [2008], with more than 10 000 cases
and 5 deaths reported so far, according to the HCMC Preventive Health
Center. Now, 242 out of around 320 wards and communes in the city
have reported outbreaks of the disease.

Nguyen Tran Chinh, director of the HCMC Hospital for Tropical
Diseases said last month [September 2008] they admitted 1000 adults
and 532 children with dengue, nearly a 300 percent increase compared
to the previous year [2007]. This month [October 2008], 1164 more
patients have been hospitalized, while last October [2007], 716 were admitted.

More than 100 in-patients were undergoing treatment at the hospital
on Wednesday [22 Oct 2008] night. Dr Nguyen Thi Kim Loan of the
hospital's Pediatrician Department A said 42 children were currently
being treated for dengue and 7 to 8 of them were in danger of going into shock.

Since the department has just 38 beds, 2 to 3 patients have to share
a single bed, while some even have to sleep on the floor or along
corridors when the department is overcrowded. Sometimes it looks like
a refugee camp, Loan said.

The hospital's Pediatric Department B specializes in treating
patients with blood poisoning (septicemia), but has now had to admit
dengue fever patients, as the dengue department is overloaded, said
nurse Le My Tien.

Tran Thi Thuy, deputy head of Children Hospital No. 2's Infectious
Disease Department, said on Thursday [23 Oct 2008] that since the end
of November 2007, they have admitted 718 children, a 20 percent
year-on-year increase. 80 percent of patients were from HCMC, mainly
District 2 and the suburban districts of Thu Duc, Go Vap, and Binh Thanh.

The department admits between 30 and 60 patients per day, Thuy said.
Each day, there are between 100 and 130 in-patients, of which 10-12
percent are in critical condition. On Wednesday [22 Oct 2008], 15
children with dengue were listed in critical condition in the
hospital. Some also had to share beds.

Dr Phan Tu Quy of the Hospital for Tropical Diseases Pediatric
Recuperation Department said within the 1st 3 weeks of this month
[October 2008], they admitted 50 children suffering shock due to
dengue. Last month [September 2008], the department admitted 86 similar cases.

The signs and symptoms of dengue fever patients are also showing more
complications than before, according to doctors.

More patients are listed in critical condition and are suffering
longer bouts of fever, up to 10 days in some cases. Bloody diarrhea,
loss of consciousness, respiratory failure, and problems with the
liver, kidneys, and brain are other symptoms cropping up in greater
numbers than before.

Lam Thi My, deputy head of Children Hospital No. 1's Dengue Fever
Department, said numbers of dengue patients had never been so high at
this time of year before. Recently, babies less than 3 months old
have also been coming in with dengue fever, said My.

According to the HCMC Preventive Health Center, efforts to curb the
disease from June [2008] to August [2008] have been largely
ineffective. Until [25 Sep 2008], more than 56 100 cases of dengue
fever and 52 deaths had been reported nationwide, the Ministry of
Health reported.

While the number of cases nationally has decreased by 22 percent, and
deaths have decreased by 15 percent year-on-year, 13 provinces and
cities have suffered from greater outbreaks than in previous years.
The southern provinces of Ca Mau and Binh Phuoc and the central
province of Nghe An are among the localities with the highest rates,
including deaths.

Nguyen Thi Thu Ha, vice chairwoman of the HCMC Peoples Committee, has
ordered local agencies to take better measures to reduce the
incidence of dengue.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-MBDS <promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[Dengue outbreaks are still being reporting in Viet Nam, with more
than 10 000 cases and 5 deaths reported from Ho Chi Minh City alone.
As of 25 Sep 2008, more than 56 100 cases and 52 deaths of dengue
fever had been reported nationwide in 2008. Central Nghe An province
had detected 687 cases of dengue fever during 2008 (see prior
PRO/MBDS posting Dengue - Viet Nam (15): Nghe An 20081014.3250).

According to a newswire on dengue fever in Viet Nam dated 25 Oct
2007, nearly 80 000 cases with 68 fatalities had occurred nationwide
since the beginning of 2007 (see prior PRO/MBDS posting Dengue - Viet
Nam (15) 20071025.3469). During October 2007, the hospitals from Ho
Chi Minh City had reported the overloading of dengue fever patients,
with an average of around 70-100 dengue fever cases per week (see
prior PRO/MBDS posting Dengue - Viet Nam (14): adults, RFI 20071012.3354).

Recently, Yunnan province from China reported 68 cases of dengue
fever, while most of the cases were reported to be imported (see
prior PRO/MBDS posting Dengue - China (05): Yunnan 20081016.3274).

For maps of Viet Nam with provinces, see
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/vietnam_admin01.jpg> and
<http://www.angelfire.com/co/hongnam/vnmap.html>.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Viet Nam can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=14.9,108.5,5>.
This map shows other outbreaks in Viet Nam and surrounding countries
that have been reported on ProMED-mail. The postings can be directly
accessed through this map. - Mod.YMA

The newswire above is very curious, as the information gives the
demographic breakdown of cases reported from HCMC during the month of
September 2008 as 1000 adults and 532 children. If this is not a
typographical error, it is a complete change from what is usually
seen in Viet Nam, where the preponderance of cases usually occurs in
children. Earlier PRO/MBDS reports have commented on the increase in
adult dengue fever cases seen, but this large disparity with almost
twice as many cases in adults than children reported during September
2008 is cause for reflection: either it is the appearance of a strain
of dengue virus that has been absent from HCMC for many years or is
just appearing there for the 1st time; or the possibility is that not
all of these reported cases are attributable to dengue virus
infection but might well be another viral infection such as
chikungunya virus infection. Chikungunya virus has been circulating
in Southeast Asia this year 2008, with cases identified in Malaysia,
Singapore, and now in Thailand (see prior PRO/MBDS posting
Chikungunya - Thailand, Malaysia: Thailand, conf. 20081026.3380).

That being said, it is also curious that the newswire mentions the
increased proportion of childhood cases presenting with serious
manifestations of dengue virus infection -- with dengue hemorrhagic
syndrome and dengue shock syndrome. PRO/MBDS would very much
appreciate more information on the virology investigations of this
outbreak -- which dengue virus type(s) have been prevalent this year
in comparison with the last few years.

More information on results of laboratory testing on the adult cases
of dengue reported from HCMC would be greatly appreciated. - Mod.MPP]
